{"finish_reason":"stop","index":0,"logprobs":null,"message":{"content":"Punitive Damages - Individual and Corporate Defendants (Corporate Liability Based on Acts of Named Individual) - Bifurcated Trial (Second Phase) has been replaced by a more current version. You can find the updated version after the following explanation.   

In a separate phase of the trial, you will determine whether defendant is liable for punitive damages. Punitive damages are not awarded to compensate a plaintiff for harm suffered, but rather to punish the defendant for its wrongful conduct and to deter such conduct in the future. To impose punitive damages on a corporation based upon acts of a named individual, you must find that the acts of the individual were willful and malicious or showed an evil motive or reckless indifference to the rights of others.    
The Texas Civil Jury Instructions Committee has revised its punitive damages instructions. One reason for the revision is that Senate Bill 5, recently enacted by the 77th Legislature, amended Chapter 41 of the Texas Civil Practice and Remedies Code to specify two components of a punitive damage award: a penalty and an amount for litigation expenses. Senate Bill 5 also requires a separate jury finding for each of these components. For further information, see the Committee Note accompanying the revised instructions.","refusal":null,"role":"assistant","annotations":[],"audio":null,"function_call":null,"tool_calls":null}}
